q {
Q:"If \\(\\sin^{-1}x + \\sin^{-1}y + \\sin^{-1}z = \\frac{3\\pi}{2}\\) then the value of \\(x^9 + y^9 + z^9 - \\frac{1}{x^9 y^9 z^9}\\) is equal to:"
A:"c"
O:a) "0", b) "1", c) "2", d) "3"
R:"The maximum value of \\(\\sin^{-1}\\theta\\) is \\(\\pi/2\\). For the sum to be \\(3\\pi/2\\), each term must be \\(\\pi/2\\), so \\(x=y=z=1\\). Substituting gives \\(1+1+1 - 1 = 2\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Let \\(p, q, r\\) be the sides opposite to the angle \\(P,Q,R\\) respectively in a triangle \\(PQR\\). If \\(r^2 \\sin P \\sin Q = pq\\) then the triangle is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "Equilateral", b) "Acute angled but not equilateral", c) "Obtuse angled if \\(\\sin\\)", d) "Right angled"
R:"Using sine rule \\(p=k\\sin P, q=k\\sin Q, r=k\\sin R\\). Substitution yields \\(\\sin^2 R = 1 \\Rightarrow R = 90^\\circ\\). Hence, right angled."
}

q {
Q:"Let \\(p, q\\), and \\(r\\) be sides opposite to the angles \\(P, Q, R\\) respectively in a triangle \\(PQR\\). Then \\(2 pr\\sin\\left(\\frac{P-Q+R}{2}\\right)\\) equals:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(p^2+q^2+r^2\\)", b) "\\(p^2+r^2-q^2\\)", c) "\\(q^2+r^2-p^2\\)", d) "\\(p^2+q^2-r^2\\)"
R:"Since \\(P+R = \\pi - Q\\), the angle becomes \\(\\frac{\\pi}{2} - Q\\). Thus, \\(\\sin(\\dots) = \\cos Q\\). By cosine rule, \\(2pr \\cos Q = p^2+r^2-q^2\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Let \\(P(2,-3)\\), \\(Q(-2, 1)\\) be the vertices of the triangle \\(PQR\\). If the centroid of \\(\\Delta PQR\\) lies on the line \\(2x+3y = 1\\), then the locus of \\(R\\) is:"
A:"a"
O:a) "\\(2x+3y=9\\)", b) "\\(2x-3y=9\\)", c) "\\(3x+2y=5\\)", d) "\\(3x-2y=5\\)"
R:"Centroid \\(G = (h/3, (k-2)/3)\\). Substituting into line eq: \\(2(h/3) + 3((k-2)/3) = 1 \\Rightarrow 2h+3k=9\\). Locus: \\(2x+3y=9\\)."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(n(A) = m\\), then \\(n(P(A)) =\\)"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\(2^n\\)", b) "\\(2n\\)", c) "\\(2^m\\)", d) "\\(2m\\)"
R:"Number of subsets of a set with \\(m\\) elements is \\(2^m\\)."
}

q {
Q:"If \\(f\\) is a real-valued differentiable function such that \\(f(x) f'(x) < 0\\) for all real \\(x\\), then:"
A:"d"
O:a) "\\(F(x)\\) must be an increasing function", b) "\\(F(x)\\) must be an decreasing function", c) "\\(|F(x)|\\) must be an increasing function", d) "\\(|F(x)|\\) must be an decreasing function"
R:"If \\(f>0\\), \\(f'<0\\) (decreasing). If \\(f<0\\), \\(f'>0\\) (increasing towards 0). In both cases, magnitude \\(|f(x)|\\) decreases."
}

q {
Q:"Role's theorem is applicable in the interval \\([-2,2]\\) for the function:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(F(x)=x^3\\)", b) "\\(F(x)=4x^4\\)", c) "\\(F(x)=2x^3+3\\)", d) "\\(F(x)=\\pi|x|\\)"R:"\\(F(-2)=F(2)=64\\) and \\(F\\) is differentiable everywhere. Other options fail either equality or differentiability."
}

q {
Q:"The solution of \\(25 \\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} -10\\frac{dy}{dx} + y = 0\\), \\(y(0)=1, y(1)=2e^{1/5}\\) is:"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\(y = e^{5x} + e^{-5x}\\)", b) "\\(y = (1+x)e^{5x}\\)", c) "\\(y = (1+x)e^{x/5}\\)", d) "\\(y = (1+x)e^{-x/5}\\)"
R:"Repeated root \\(m=1/5\\). Solution \\(y=(c_1+c_2x)e^{x/5}\\). Conditions yield \\(c_1=1, c_2=1\\)."
}

q {
Q:"Let \\(P\\) be the midpoint of a chord joining the vertex of the parabola \\(y^2 = 8x\\) to another point on it. Then the locus of \\(P\\) is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(y^2 = 2x\\)", b) "\\(y^2 = 4x\\)", c) "\\(x^2/4 + y^2 = 1\\)", d) "\\(x^2 + y^2/4 = 1\\)"
R:"Let point be \\((x_1,y_1)\\). Midpoint \\((h,k) \\Rightarrow x_1=2h, y_1=2k\\). On parabola: \\((2k)^2=8(2h) \\Rightarrow k^2=4h\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The line \\(x=2y\\) intersects the ellipse \\(\\frac{x^2}{4} + y^2 = 1\\) at the point \\(P\\) and \\(Q\\). The equation of the circle with \\(PQ\\) as diameter is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "\\(x^2 + y^2 = 1/2\\)", b) "\\(x^2 + y^2 = 1\\)", c) "\\(x^2 + y^2 = 2\\)", d) "\\(x^2 + y^2 = 5/2\\)"
R:"Points are \\((\\pm\\sqrt{2}, \\pm1/\\sqrt{2})\\). Center \\((0,0)\\), radius squared \\(= 2+1/2=5/2\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The eccentric angle in the first quadrant of a point on the ellipse \\(\\frac{x^2}{10} + \\frac{y^2}{8} = 1\\) at a distance 3 units from the center of the ellipse is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "\\(\\pi/6\\)", b) "\\(\\pi/4\\)", c) "\\(\\pi/3\\)", d) "\\(\\pi/2\\)"
R:"Point \\((\\sqrt{10}\\cos\\theta, \\sqrt{8}\\sin\\theta)\\). Distance sq: \\(10\\cos^2\\theta+8\\sin^2\\theta=9 \\Rightarrow 2\\cos^2\\theta=1 \\Rightarrow \\theta=\\pi/4\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The transverse axis of a hyperbola is along the x-axis and its length is \\(2a\\). The vertex of the hyperbola bisects the line segment joining the center and the focus. The equation of the hyperbola is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "\\(6x^2-y^2=3a^2\\)", b) "\\(x^2-3y^2=3a^2\\)", c) "\\(x^2-6y^2=3a^2\\)", d) "\\(3x^2-y^2=3a^2\\)"
R:"\\(a = ae/2 \\Rightarrow e=2\\). \\(b^2 = a^2(e^2-1) = 3a^2\\). Eq: \\(x^2/a^2 - y^2/3a^2 = 1 \\Rightarrow 3x^2-y^2=3a^2\\)."
}

q {
Q:"A point moves in such a way that the difference of its distance from two points \\((8, 0)\\) and \\((-8, 0)\\) always remains 4. Then the locus of the point is:"
A:"d"
O:a) "A circle", b) "A parabola", c) "An ellipse", d) "A hyperbola"
R:"By definition, constant difference of distances from two foci defines a hyperbola."
}

q {
Q:"The number of integer values of \\(m\\), for which the x-coordinate of the point of intersection of the lines \\(3x+4y=9\\) and \\(y=mx+1\\) is also an integer is:"
A:"b"
O:a) "0", b) "2", c) "4", d) "1"
R:"\\(x = 5/(3+4m)\\). For integer \\(x\\), \\(3+4m\\) divides 5. Yields \\(m=-1, -2\\). Two values."}

q {
Q:"If a straight line passes through the point \\((\\alpha,\\beta)\\) and the portion of the line intercepted between the axes is divided equally at the point, then \\(x/\\alpha + y/\\beta\\) is:"
A:"c"
O:a) "0", b) "1", c) "2", d) "4"
R:"Intercepts are \\((2\\alpha, 0)\\) and \\((0, 2\\beta)\\). Eq: \\(x/2\\alpha + y/2\\beta = 1 \\Rightarrow x/\\alpha + y/\\beta = 2\\)."
}

q {
Q:"The maximum value of \\(|z|\\) when the complex number \\(z\\) satisfies the condition \\(|z+2/z|=2\\) is:"
A:"c"
O:a) "\\(\\sqrt{3}\\)", b) "\\(\\sqrt{3}+\\sqrt{2}\\)", c) "\\(\\sqrt{3}+1\\)", d) "\\(\\sqrt{3}-1\\)"
R:"\\(|z| - |2/z| \\le 2 \\Rightarrow r^2 - 2r - 2 \\le 0 \\Rightarrow r \\le 1+\\sqrt{3}\\)."
}

q {
